column14:
Here's a brief overview of what we do to Baxter BXA-HBA ovens...
 
We completely rebuild the top-end with new parts. At a minimum, these are the new parts we install regardless of the condition of the existing parts:
 
01-1000V0-00054BEARING, FLUOROGOLD W/FLANGE01-1000V0-00055BEARING, ROTATOR SHAFT (2)01-1000V0-00068WASHER,THRUST-ROTATOR01-1000V3-00085SPROCKET, #35B,13T, NO KEYWAY01-1000V3-00087CHAIN PER INCH PC=20IN01-1000V3-00088LINK, CONNECTING - #3501-1000V8-00056BLADE, FAN-400 CFM (5" DIA,5 W01-1M2265-00001CLUTCH, SLIDE - LIFTER01-1M1927-00001PLATE, TEFLON01-1M2264-00001COLLAR, SET - LIFTER01-1M2228-00001SPROCKET, ROTATOR - LIFTER
 
*If the drive motor shows any evidence of leaking oil, we replace it with a new motor.
*Door gasket and door sweep are replaced with new parts.
*We check the water solenoid for operation and verify that all water lines are clear. We also check and clear both drains.
*We check the outside and inside door handles for proper operation and replace if necessary.
*After verifying the PC board is fully operational, we re-seal the outside edges of the board with silicon.
*We check the galvanized plate under the heat exchanger and if rust is detected we replace the plate with 20 ga. stainless steel plate.
*Inshot burner is completely dismantled and cleaned. Crossovers are cleaned with compressed air.
*Entire oven is pressure washed with 300 deg. steam at 3500 psi.
[Rick Evans]
column19: Note: Here's a brief overview of what we do to Baxter BX...

****************************
Quote #: 18983 sent on two pre-owned baxter ovensvendor is Taskaa cost is 15k for both******************[Rick Evans]

What year was this oven built/manufactured?
1987'   but was used very little per day.
How good of a shape is it init looks like it is in fairly good cond judging by the photo.
We go through each piece of equipment and clean and test and replace anything that is 20% or more worn.
Is all of the mechanical located in the front of the oven? Do the sides/ends need to be accessible for any reason?
Back and sides can be 1 away from the walls, all service access is from the front.
As I remember it the Baxter has the neat feature of auto stop at the next shelf when loading, is that correct and does that work?
This is correct
Your price for removal, does that include disposal?
No, you will need a dumpster on site, (you might try calling a local metal scrap guy that might take it down for free if he gets the metal)
Where would your crew and this piece of equipment be coming from?
We have a 60,000sq foot shop in Tipton, MO   my friend out of NY would be the installer
How big is the largest piece?
Baxter mfg. this oven so everything will fit through a standard single door
This oven will be installed in the basement of our facility as is the MM.
Want to be sure that it will actually fit down the stairwell. The MM was tight, we actually had to notch a brick in the masonry to get it in.
I would need to see pictures and the install price would go up, if our installer needs to take this down stairs.
Can we get a copy of the spec sheets to locate the gas input and the exhaust flue/stack.
attached[Rick Evans]

column14:
1.What length is the cutting blade?
I will have to get exact dimensions on the blade.  But we were using it to cut both round cakes up to 10 in diameter 3 in height.  It also cut sheet cakes and brownies in foil pans and bakeable cardboard.  We were using a 12x17 size.
2.Will this machine cut Round cakes as well as sheet pans?
Yes it currently does and can be programmed to do between 4-24 cuts on rounds and many different cut dimensions on the square sheet products
3.What accessories come with the machine Eg: cutting templates etc.
I think we have about 4-5 different platens that we had designed for our product... it may be a few more.  We would send them all with the machine.
4.Will this machine cut cake slabs that have been baked in a cardboard bake able box?
You can use different material to bake in, including foil as it will not harm the blade.  
5.Can this machine be fitted with multiple blades as the brochure suggests?
I would have to check on this one but I assume it could be done.
6.Is the Touch screen in English?
Yes
7.How many programs can the machine take for different product types?
I would have to check on the exact number but I know we have probably 30 programs in there already.
8.What is the overall condition of the machine?
We purchased the machine new I am pretty sure it was 2005.  It is in great shape and low hours for its age.  Our product mix has changed and we are open to selling it.
I will have to get some pictures for you.
[Rick Evans]

PREFER GAS OR ELECT: Please Choose

ELECTRICAL REQUIREMENTS: Voltage: 220 V Frequency: 50 Hz Power sockets: type C / F
PURCHASE TIME FRAME: As soon as possible

PRIMARY PRODUCTS: Georgian Baked Items: Georgian cuisine features a variety of dough-based dishes. One of the main national dishes of Georgian cuisine is mchadi, nosey corn fritters which according to Georgian culinary traditions need to be served with Imeretian cheese or Suluguni cheese. The secret of good baking and inimitable taste of mchadi is in corn meal. The best corn in Georgia is thought to grow in the township of Abashi in the west of the country. There is a popular belief among the Georgians, that the mchadi will be more delicious if to bake the fritters from the flour, ground in a water-driven mill. Georgia has many recipes to prepare mchadi. Every housewife adds something of her own, but the main ingredients of this remarkable Georgian bread remain unchanged: fine corn flour, salt, vegetable oil and naturally Imeretian cheese or Suluguni. Perhaps, the best-known Georgian national dish is khachapuri, a flat cake (pie) with cheese, meat or steamed fish. Sometimes khachapuri is baked using yeast-containing dough, but traditionally khachapuri is baked using matsoni (sour milk). Traditional pie filler for khachapuri is Imeretian cheese (other than Suluguni). Every region in Georgia has its traditions to cook this dish. Together with khachapuri, flat pies with French bean   lobiani and meat   kubdari are traditional in Georgia. Of special note is Georgian pie with cheese   achma, cooked from an ample quantity of laminated dough, which is slightly cooked. As far as filler concerns, the same Suluguni and Ossetian cheese are used for it. The peculiarity of this national dish is that the dough is not sweet while the cheese should be salted. Following the old Georgian traditions, achma is served hot. 
SEND QUOTE: YES
BEST EMAIL FORMAT: Rich Text E-Mails O.K.
HOW DID YOU HEAR OF US: Search Engine
QUESTIONS COMMENTS:   The idea is to build a Central Hub in Georgia for all items requested, including the Service Department.   Prices and quality must compete with the current import from Turkey and China.   The Demand is from hundreds of bakeries across the country, and is high.

Hi - Darren,
I wanted to let you know that Keith Barry came in this morning and picked up his case that he bought through your company.
I have attached photos, showing the case before loading and how it looked on his open trailer.  We need to advise you that when he left here, the case was not completely covered and it was raining here.  Keith was advised that the case must be covered because the base is made from flakeboard with laminate on the exterior, and he was advised if the base gets wet it will cause the boards to swell & the laminate to bubble / come loose.  He did ask for directions to the closes Dollar General Store so he could buy additional tarps.
He was also advised that the unit must be properly strapped down; he brought 3 straps and was working on putting the last two on when I took the last photo.
NOTE:  
1.Our Shipping Department said he failed to come back in and sign our copy of the BOL before he left.
2.Remember ownership / liability for the case transfers to you and your customer when the case is loaded in his vehicle / trailer.  (FOB Origin)
We hope he makes it back to Kansas without any issues.[Darren Sydorko]

Michael,
Stu finally found the issue in your bakery.
You have a negative air issue and the return air is coming down the oven stack blowing out the flame.  Just like blowing out a candle on a birthday cake.
You need to call an HVAC installer and get your air in the bakery to a static situation.
I know the oven was working fine, and we finally found the issue..  
We have spent over 2,000.00 because your bakery has a negative air issue.  Fyi.
Stu said you have  hood in the bakery that is sucking air out, where is the return air for this?   Right now the return air is coming down the exhaust on the oven.  (this needs to be resolved by an HVAC contractor)
Until this is fixed by them    open a door or large window, to help in getting the return air inside the bakery.
Feel free to call me, if you need further explanation on a negative air pressure situation in a bakery.
Rick Evans[Rick Evans]

Hi Rick,
Convection oven pricing to BCOM would be as follows:
SCENARIO 1 - full containers (40'  container = 40 ovens, 20'  container = 20 ovens) delivered directly from Shanghai to Tipton, MO.  BCOM receives and QCs the ovens, BCOM covers warranty.
Oven price: $2,200 each PLUS FREIGHT and port charges.  Price includes legs.
Inbound freight, processing charges, etc. for a 20'  container (20 ovens) from China to Tipton, MO:  $4,600 - $5,400 (approximate - rates fluctuate)
Inbound freight, processing charges, etc. for a 40'  container (40 ovens) from China to Tipton, MO:  $5,300 - $6,100 (approximate - rates fluctuate)
Total Scenario 1 per-unit landed cost to BCOM (approximately) = $2,353 (40 ovens) - $2,470 (20 ovens)
SCENARIO 2:  LBC receives and QC' s the ovens.  LBC holds ovens in inventory and ships to BCOM in small quantities.  BCOM covers warranty.
Oven Price: $2,500 each plus inbound freight and port charges, plus outbound freight to Tipton, MO.  Price includes legs.
Approximate inbound freight, etc. to LBC = $85 - $100/oven (based on full container).
Approximate outbound freight LBC to Tipton, MO: 1 oven = $245; 5 ovens = $878; 10 ovens = $1,526
Total Scenario 2 per-unit landed cost to BCOM: $2,753 (10 ovens) - $2,845 (one oven)
Ultimately, SCENARIO 1 is where we would like to be.  We would start with SCENARIO 2 and transition to SCENARIO 1 over time.
Regarding service parts, we will provide BCOM with a price list of standard service parts for the convection ovens, along with alternate sourcing information where available so they can decide whether to purchase parts from LBC or from alternate sources.  I' ll have to put that together and send it separately over the next week.
Please let me know if you have any questions.
Thanks,  Steve and Brian[Rick Evans]
